The majority of responses were from those working in free-standing children’s hospitals (61%) and university hospitals (60%). The majority of the postoperative care was reported to be delivered in a cardiac intensive care unit (CICU; Figure 1
). Those working in programs that performed over 300 open heart surgeries a year made up almost half of the responses (Figure 2
). Nearly half of those responding stated they were trained in critical care or the combination of critical care and cardiology (Figure 3
). Just fewer than 20% were surgeons. A third of those responding to this survey reported they were members of the pediatric cardiac intensive care society.

Over 90% of those responding to our survey stated that they used serial lactate monitoring for patients recovering after congenital heart surgery (Table 2
). Almost 90% stated they used some type of NIRS monitoring. Lactate monitoring performed only when clinically indicated was a preferred strategy for monitoring patients that few clinicians reported to use. Serial lactate monitoring was the considered the single best indicator of cardiovascular well-being after congenital heart surgery, followed by multisite NIRS and continuous SvO2 monitoring. The majority of lactate measurements (68%) were performed in the ICU as opposed to a remote laboratory located outside of the ICU (Figure 4
). Measurement of blood lactate levels in the ICU was accomplished with either a blood gas machine located in the ICU or a point-of-care testing device. The least frequently utilized techniques for assessing cardiovascular well-being included single-site NIRS, noninvasive SvO2, continuous SvO2 monitoring, and monitoring of cardiac output (measured either invasively or noninvasively).
